            "itemType": "journalArticle",
            "title": "Tropical Rainforests as Reservoirs for Emerging Zoonoses",
            "creators": [
                {
                    "creatorType": "author",
                    "firstName": "Fabian",
                    "lastName": "Leendertz"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "The last tropical rainforests are important reservoirs for yet unknown pathogens with zoonotic potential. Human intrusion into these former remote habitats through deforestation and bush meat hunting leads to an increased contact between humans and wildlife, and between humans and insect vectors (Leendertz et al., 2006; Jones et al., 2008; Gillespie et al., 2009). In the course of our research on pathogen transmission in this type of ecosystem, samples from non-human primates and other nammalian hosts living in tropical rainforests as well as humans living around rainforests are collected and analysed at the Robert Koch-Institut. One of the aims of our studies is to evaluate the risk of emergence of new zoonoses in the human population. We specifically focus on screening humans with high exposure to blood and organs of wild primates through bushmeat hunting and handling, but pathogen transmission from other possible hosts are also analysed. Chimpanzees can be seen as a \"natural system\" to study disease transmission among primates. In the last years we have shown that simian retroviruses, such as the Simian T-Cell Leukemia Virus-1 (STLV-1) and Foamy-Viruses (SFV) are transmitted from one non-human primate to another. Based on molecular epidemiological findings as well as prevalence data in different age classes of wild chimpanzees, we could show that the main transmission of these viruses is through the hunter-prey relationship that exists between red colobus monkeys and chimpanzees (Leendertz et al., 2004a, b; Leendertz et al., 2008). These findings in wild primates, which are known to be hunted by humans, inspired us to perform a study focused on the human population in the area together with the Institut Pasteur Cote d'Ivoire, and we found evidence of virus transmission from non-human primates to humans. Furthermore, we investigated several outbreaks of respiratory diseases in wild chimpanzees. In necropsy samples from deceased chimpanzees we detected two new strains of S. pneumoniae (Chi et al., 2007). In addition, the chimpanzees were infected with human paramyxoviruses (Kondgen et al., 2008). This was the first description of anthropoozonotic transmission of human respiratory viruses to great apes, identifying that human diseases are an important threat to these endangered species. In order to investigate the influence of ecological changes on the prevalence of mosquitoes and arboviruses, we systematically captured mosquitoes in and around tropical rainforests with different degrees of ecological changes. Firstly, we detected new viruses of the families Flavi-, Bunya- and Coronaviruses (Junglen et al., 2009), Secondly, we could show that ecological changes had a dramatic influence on the distribution and prevalence of mosquito and viruses, indicating that disturbance of the rainforest increases the risk of transmission of arboviruses to the human population (Junglen et al., in print).",
